{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a5e12f6a-a577-43c7-abdf-1c132517bc26","content":"Here's the recommended approach using `dotnet-trace` with the CPU profiling profile:\n\n### 1. Install the tool inside the pod\n\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n### 2. Collect the trace\n\n```bash\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a 30-second CPU trace (speedscope format is portable)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30 -o /tmp/trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### 3. Copy it out\n\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/tmp/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### 4. Analyze\n\n- **Visual Studio** — open the `.nettrace` file directly.\n- **Speedscope** — convert first: `dotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format speedscope`, then open at [speedscope.app](https://speedscope.app).\n- **PerfView** (Windows) — opens `.nettrace` natively.\n\n### Tips\n\n- If you can't install tools (distroless/read-only), use **dotnet-monitor** as a sidecar instead — it exposes a `/trace` HTTP endpoint.\n- For a lower-level perf view, `perf record -g -p <PID>` works too if `perf` is available, but `dotnet-trace` gives you managed stack frames out of the box.\n- Use `--buffersize 256` if the default buffer is too small under heavy load.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"245a8898-ba66-4524-a981-e32e86353e9a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I can answer this from knowledge without needing to search the codebase.","outputTokens":475,"requestId":"6010:12ABA3:29D04A:315400:69EAC5FB"},"id":"7e8160d7-722a-44c9-a4df-2cd25d3ff47c","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:23:19.493Z","parentId":"f90c186e-fb28-4605-a13b-5c9aeb4209c6"}
